<HEADLINE>
Gulf stocks fall sharply on Lehman Brothers news
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stock markets across the energy-rich Gulf fell sharply on Monday,
shedding up to seven percent of their value on the Lehman
Brothers bankruptcy and a big drop in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
There was swift reaction in Kuwait where the Kuwait Investment
Authority (KIA) decided to inject fresh funds into the sagging
bourse and parliament urged government intervention.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi bourse, the largest in the Arab world, fell 6.5 percent
at close of trading as the Tadawul All-Shares Index (TASI)
finished at 7,255.15 points. It has lost 34.3 percent since the
start of the year.
</P>
<P>
There were similar drops in other Gulf stock markets, which have
already been reeling under yet another correction wave.
</P>
<P>
"Two factors are pulling the Gulf bourses down -- the
psychological impact of the Lehman Brothers issue and the sharp
fall in oil prices," said Kuwaiti financial analyst Ali al-
Nimesh.
</P>
<P>
Lehman Brothers -- the fourth largest investment bank in the
United States -- shook the world's financial system on Monday by
seeking bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices, meanwhile, tumbled below 93 dollars a barrel in
London, their lowest level since February, on the prospect of
weaker demand for energy amid the worsening financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Stock Exchange, the second largest in the Arab world,
closed down 3.8 percent at 12,360.20 points. It shed 488 points,
the largest points loss on a single day, dropping below the 2007
close for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
The KSE Index, which has been sliding continuously since August
20, is now 1.6 percent below last year's close of 12,558.80
points and 21 percent below its all-time high of 15,654.80 points
set on June 24. The market has been reeling under a liquidity
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It's a real tsunami in our market. We don't know whether what's
happening is real or a dream," Kuwaiti dealer Fuad al-Awadh told
AFP soon after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
KIA, which manages more than 250 billion dollars on behalf of the
state, said it has decided to pump an unspecified amount of money
into investment funds to buy shares in a bid to boost the falling
market.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Kuwaiti parliament's financial affairs
committee, Nasser al- Sane, said the committee will discuss "the
bourse collapse" with the ministers of commerce and finance on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Parliament speaker Jassem al-Khorafi called on the government to
step in to halt the slide in the bourse.
</P>
<P>
The Doha Securities Market shed 7.01 percent to finish at
8,216.71 points, down 14.2 percent on last year's close of
9,580.45 points. For most of the year, it was trading above the
10,000-point mark.
</P>
<P>
In the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the Abu Dhabi Securities
Exchange dived 4.35 percent to 3,754.49 points. It has so far
lost 17.5 percent from its 2007 close of 4,551.80 points.
</P>
<P>
The index of the other UAE bourse, Dubai Financial Market,
finished at 4,044.27 points, down 1.7 percent, slightly
recovering from bigger losses during trading. The DFM Index is
31.8 percent below last year's close.
</P>
<P>
The two UAE bourses have been falling in recent weeks because of
a drop in the shares of giant real estate companies which are
market leaders.
</P>
<P>
The combined capitalisation of the five bourses in addition to
the tiny stock markets of Bahrain and Oman has dropped by close
to 200 billion dollars from their value at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The seven bourses' capitalisation stood at 1.116 trillion dollars
on December 31.
</P>
